Q. What is Optional in Java?

-Optional is a special class in Java (introduced in Java 8) that represents a value that might be present or
absent.
-Instead of using null to indicate “no value,” you use an Optional object.

Q.Why Use Optional?

a.Helps avoid NullPointerException (errors when you use a variable that’s null).
b.Makes your code clearer: it’s obvious when a value might be missing.

How to Use Optional in Java

1. Creating an Optional

a.With a value:

Ex:
Optional<String> name = Optional.of("Alice");

b. Without a value (empty):

Ex:
Optional<String> name = Optional.empty();

c.Maybe a value (could be null):

Ex:
Optional<String> name = Optional.ofNullable(possibleName);

2. Checking if a Value is Present

Ex:
if (name.isPresent()) {
    System.out.println("Name: " + name.get());
} else {
    System.out.println("No name provided");
}

3. Using a Default Value

String displayName = name.orElse("Guest");
System.out.println(displayName); // Prints "Alice" or "Guest"

4. Using Lambda Expressions

name.ifPresent(n -> System.out.println("Hello, " + n));

Only prints if there’s a value.

5. Chaining with map and flatMap

Optional<String> upperName = name.map(n -> n.toUpperCase());

Transforms the value if present.


Q. Why Not Just Use null?

(i)  Optional makes it clear that a value might be missing.
(ii) Forces you to handle the missing case, reducing bugs.

Summary:

(i)   Optional is a container for a value that might be present or absent.
(ii)  Use it to avoid null and make your code safer.
(iii) Always check or handle the case where the value is missing.


More detailed description of Optional:

1. What is Optional<T> in Java?

(i)  Optional<T> is a container object introduced in Java 8 to represent the presence or absence of a value.
(ii) Its main goal is to avoid NullPointerException by making the possibility of missing values explicit in
your code.
(iii) It is most commonly used as a return type for methods that might not always return a value.

2. Creating Optionals:

There are three main ways to create an Optional:

// 1. Optional.of(value) - value must not be null
Optional<String> opt1 = Optional.of("Hello");

// 2. Optional.ofNullable(value) - value can be null
Optional<String> opt2 = Optional.ofNullable(possibleNull);

// 3. Optional.empty() - creates an empty Optional
Optional<String> opt3 = Optional.empty();


(i)   Optional.of(value) throws a NullPointerException if value is null.
(ii)  Optional.ofNullable(value) is safe for possibly null values.
(iii) Optional.empty() is used to explicitly create an empty Optional.


3. Checking for Value Presence:

(i)  isPresent(): Returns true if a value is present, false otherwise.
(ii) isEmpty(): (Java 11+) Returns true if no value is present.


Optional<String> opt = Optional.of("Java");
if (opt.isPresent()) {
    System.out.println(opt.get());
}


4. Retrieving Values:

(i)   get(): Returns the value if present, else throws NoSuchElementException. Use with caution!
(ii)  orElse(defaultValue): Returns the value if present, else returns defaultValue.
(iii) orElseGet(Supplier): Returns the value if present, else calls the supplier to get a value.
(iv)  orElseThrow(): Throws NoSuchElementException if value is absent.
(v)   orElseThrow(Supplier): Throws a custom exception if value is absent.

Ex:
-String name = Optional.ofNullable(null).orElse("Default");
-String name2 = Optional.ofNullable(null).orElseGet(() -> "GeneratedDefault");
-String name3 = Optional.ofNullable(null).orElseThrow(() -> new IllegalArgumentException("No value!"));

5. Conditional Actions:
(i)ifPresent(Consumer): Executes the consumer if a value is present.
(ii)ifPresentOrElse(Consumer, Runnable): (Java 9+) Executes consumer if present, else runs the runnable.

Ex:
Optional<String> opt = Optional.of("Java");
opt.ifPresent(val -> System.out.println("Value: " + val));

Optional<String> emptyOpt = Optional.empty();
emptyOpt.ifPresentOrElse(
    val -> System.out.println("Value: " + val),
    () -> System.out.println("No value present")
);


6. Transforming and Filtering Optionals:

(i)   map(Function): Applies a function to the value if present, returns a new Optional.
(ii)  flatMap(Function): Like map, but the function must return an Optional (avoids nested Optionals).
(iii) filter(Predicate): Returns the Optional if the value matches the predicate, else returns empty.

Ex:
Optional<String> opt = Optional.of("  Java  ");
Optional<String> trimmed = opt.map(String::trim); // Optional["Java"]

Optional<Integer> length = opt.map(String::length); // Optional[7]

Optional<String> filtered = opt.filter(s -> s.length() > 5); // Optional["  Java  "]


7. Best Practices:

(i)Use as a return type: Use Optional to signal a method might not return a value.
(ii)Avoid as fields or parameters: Don’t use Optional as class fields or method parameters.
(iii)Prefer functional methods: Use map, filter, ifPresent over isPresent + get.
(iv)Never return null Optionals: Always return Optional.empty() instead of null.
(v)Don’t overuse: Use Optional only when absence of value is a valid, expected case.

8. Common Interview Questions:

Q: Why use Optional instead of null?
A: Optional makes the possibility of missing values explicit, forces handling of absence, and helps avoid
NullPointerExceptions.

Q: What’s the difference between orElse and orElseGet?
A: orElse always evaluates its argument, even if the value is present. orElseGet only calls the supplier
if the value is absent.

Q: When should you use flatMap?
A: Use flatMap when your mapping function returns an Optional, to avoid nested Optionals.

9. Example: Using Optionals in a Repository

public Optional<User> findUserById(String id) {
    User user = database.find(id);
    return Optional.ofNullable(user);
}

// Usage
findUserById("123")
    .map(User::getName)
    .ifPresent(name -> System.out.println("User name: " + name));


10. Anti-Patterns:

(i)Don’t use Optional for every nullable value—only where it makes sense.
(ii)Don’t use Optional in collections (e.g., List<Optional<T>>), prefer empty collections or filtering.

